Create a shell program called `runloom`.

PURPOSE
  It takes a single argument -- a Python script -- and executes it on the
  system's free-threaded Python with my `pygo` C extension built and importable.

ONE-TIME SETUP / STORAGE
  1. I have a GitHub repo called `pygo`. Clone it to a location on my system
     where coding agents can't touch it (outside my normal working tree).
  2. Store any metadata the tool needs (e.g. info about installed packages) in
     that protected location too.

ON EVERY INVOCATION `runloom <script.py>`
  3. Pull the latest from the `pygo` repo so it's up to date.
  4. Find the system's free-threaded Python (the current pyenv 3.13t build).
  5. Build the C extension -- but only rebuild when something actually changed;
     otherwise reuse the existing build.
  6. Run the given script with that interpreter, passing all the flags /
     environment needed to load the built extension.

PACKAGE MANAGEMENT SUBCOMMANDS
  7. `runloom install <pkg>` -- install <pkg> in editable / developer mode
     (`pip install -e`) so it's available to all subsequent `runloom` runs.
     Provide a matching `runloom uninstall <pkg>`.
  8. Keep installed packages SEPARATE from the global interpreter that runs the
     tool itself -- they must not conflict with the existing pyenv setup, and
     they must NOT be loaded when `runloom`'s own machinery runs (only when
     running a target script).
